window.remoteQnaData = [{
  q: "N1", stem: "A patient hailing from Delhi presents with fever, arthralgia, and extensive petechial rash for 3 days. Lab investigations revealed a hemoglobin of 9 g/dL, a white blood cell count of 9000 cells/mm3, a platelet count of 20000 cells/mm3, and a prolonged bleeding time. The clotting time was normal. What is the most likely diagnosis?", ans_key: "A", options: ["Dengue", "Malaria", "Scrub typhus", "Typhoid"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2023" },
            { q: "N2", stem: "Which of the following statements is true about Trichomonas vaginalis?", ans_key: "B", options: ["It cannot be cultured", "Twitching motility is seen on wet saline mount", "Cysts are seen on wet saline mount of vaginal secretions", "It is not a sexually transmitted infection"], subject: "Microbiology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2023" },

{ q: "N336", stem: "A 52-year-old female patient presents with left-sided arm and leg weakness, right-sided facial paralysis, and difficulty with horizontal eye movements. Based on the clinical presentation, which of the following syndromes is most consistent with these symptoms?", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["Foville syndrome", "Benedict's syndrome", "Millard-Gubler syndrome", "Wallenberg syndrome"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Millard-Gubler syndrome, also known as ventral pontine syndrome, is characterized by a combination of ipsilateral cranial nerve (CN) VI and VII palsy with contralateral hemiplegia. The clinical presentation in this case—left-sided arm and leg weakness (contralateral hemiplegia), right-sided facial paralysis (ipsilateral CN VII palsy), and difficulty with horizontal eye movements (ipsilateral CN VI palsy)—is consistent with Millard-Gubler syndrome.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Foville syndrome typically affects the paramedian region, leading to ipsilateral facial paralysis, horizontal gaze palsy, and contralateral hemiplegia. However, it often includes additional symptoms like loss of conjugate gaze due to involvement of the pontine tegmentum.</li><li>Option B: Benedict's syndrome involves the midbrain (red nucleus and third nerve fascicles), leading to ipsilateral oculomotor nerve palsy and contralateral ataxia and tremor.</li><li>Option D: Wallenberg syndrome (lateral medullary syndrome) is due to a lesion in the lateral part of the medulla oblongata.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N337", stem: "A 48 year old male patient of CKD has tachycardia. An ECG is taken and shown below. What's the most likely diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjNXucb38b3RDNSN_IivYD8luJdwl4SYWXqZmIhlOGyYFLll0fTnp8AC10ZAMli4Aj3Ed277W53ZHjHh5vlMBR4ftpw2S_0QVoR65jhmI3z9qPMIL64AW2Af-9NHoVwWvoRtNa2dJCjusFgjDeq2a-9weobkN16sGLyfwt27_NuTbp5R2LBVihYUdVz2bs/s640/159909ea-9826-4991-bedf-11f3f12a7950.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Hyperkalemia", "Hypokalemia", "Hypercalcemia", "Hypocalcemia"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Chronic kidney disease (CKD) often leads to electrolyte imbalances due to impaired kidney function. Hyperkalemia is one such common imbalance, which can have significant effects on cardiac function.<br>ECG Findings in Hyperkalemia:<br>1. Tall, peaked T waves<br>2. Widened QRS complexes<br>3. Prolonged PR Interval<br>4. Flattening or absence of P waves<br>Eventually, this can lead to a sine-wave pattern and ventricular fibrillation if untreated.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: ECG findings typically include U waves, flattened or inverted T waves, and prolonged QT interval.</li><li>Option C: ECG may show a shortened QT interval.</li><li>Option D: ECG may show a prolonged QT interval.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N338", stem: "A 22 year old male patient presents with large sweaty hands, macroglossia, and frontal bossing. Select the best test for confirmation of the diagnosis:", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["GHRH levels", "IGF-1", "IGF-2", "GH levels after glucose suppression"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The best test for confirming a diagnosis of acromegaly (often caused by excess growth hormone) is measuring Insulin-like Growth Factor 1 (IGF-1). IGF-1 levels are elevated in acromegaly due to the increased secretion of growth hormone. IGF-1 is a stable marker that reflects chronic exposure to growth hormone and is therefore more reliable for diagnosis compared to intermittent measurements of growth hormone.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: GHRH levels are not typically used for the diagnosis of acromegaly.</li><li>Option C: IGF-2 is not typically used for diagnosing acromegaly.</li><li>Option D: While glucose suppression tests are used to evaluate growth hormone suppression, measuring GH levels after glucose suppression is less reliable than IGF-1 for diagnosing acromegaly.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N339", stem: "A patient with a history of Wilson's disease presents with neurological manifestations and abnormal eye findings. Which of the following is the best diagnostic modality?", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["Serum ceruloplasmin", "Urinary copper excretion", "Hepatic parenchymal demonstration of copper", "Anti-tissue transglutaminase (Anti-tTG) antibody"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The best diagnostic modality to confirm Wilson's disease, especially in the presence of neurological manifestations, is hepatic parenchymal demonstration of copper. This is usually done by performing a liver biopsy to measure the hepatic copper concentration, which is considered the gold standard for diagnosis.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Serum ceruloplasmin is often low but not the most reliable diagnostic tool as it can be low in other conditions or normal in some Wilson's patients.</li><li>Option B: 24-hour urinary copper excretion is elevated but not as definitive as hepatic copper measurement.</li><li>Option D: Associated with celiac disease, not relevant to Wilson's disease.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N340", stem: "A 28 year female patient presents with wheezing that improves with as-needed use of albuterol. Spirometry shows FEV1 ranging from 70% to 83%, and the patient experiences nighttime chest tightening twice a week. What is the most appropriate treatment?", img: "", ans_key: "D", options: ["Continue with albuterol", "Replace with salmeterol twice daily", "Start Tab prednisolone", "Add an inhaled corticosteroid"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Based on the patient's symptoms and spirometry results, the patient is likely experiencing persistent mild asthma. The FEV1 ranging from 70% to 83% suggests some airflow limitation, and nighttime symptoms occurring twice a week indicate inadequate control. Inhaled corticosteroids (ICS) are the mainstay of treatment for persistent asthma to reduce inflammation. Given the frequency of nighttime symptoms, it is necessary to step up the treatment from just using a short-acting beta-agonist as needed.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Insufficient for persistent asthma; SABA is for quick relief.</li><li>Option B: LABA should not be used alone without an ICS.</li><li>Option C: Oral corticosteroids are reserved for acute exacerbations or severe persistent asthma.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N341", stem: "A patient presents with the following laboratory values: pH 7.3, pCO2 14 mmHg, HCO3- 6 mEq/L, Na+ 136 mEq/L, Cl- 110 mEq/L. Which of the following is correct about this condition?", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis", "High anion gap metabolic acidosis", "Respiratory acidosis with metabolic alkalosis", "Respiratory alkalosis with metabolic acidosis"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Calculation of Anion Gap:<br>AG = [Na+] - ([Cl-] + [HCO3-])<br>AG = [136] - (110 + 6) = 20<br>The normal range for the anion gap is typically 8-12 mEq/L. An anion gap of 20 indicates a high anion gap metabolic acidosis.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis would have a normal AG (8-12 mEq/L).</li><li>Option C: Low pCO2 rules out respiratory acidosis; low HCO3- rules out metabolic alkalosis.</li><li>Option D: The primary disturbance is metabolic acidosis (low HCO3- and high AG), though low pCO2 suggests respiratory compensation or alkalosis, the high AG defines the type of metabolic acidosis.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N342", stem: "In a patient with type 1 diabetes at the 3rd stage of beta cell damage, which of the following conditions is most likely to be observed?", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["Autoimmune positive + normoglycemia", "Autoimmune negative + normoglycemia", "Autoimmune positive + dysglycemia", "Autoimmune negative + dysglycemia"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>In Stage 3 of type 1 diabetes, there is significant beta cell damage due to an ongoing autoimmune process, leading to dysglycemia (impaired glucose levels). At this stage, there is insufficient insulin production to maintain normal glucose levels, causing hyperglycemia, which characterizes dysglycemia.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Seen in Stage 1 (autoimmune response with normal glucose).</li><li>Option B: Not associated with type 1 diabetes (hallmark is autoimmunity).</li><li>Option D: Suggestive of type 2 diabetes (dysglycemia without autoimmunity).</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N343", stem: "A pulmonary artery hypertension patient presented with an irregularly irregular pulse with loud P2 on auscultation. Which JVP finding will be seen in this patient?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Absent a waves", "Cannon a waves", "Rapid x descent", "Rapid y descent"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The patient has pulmonary artery hypertension (PAH) and presents with an irregularly irregular pulse and a loud P2. The irregularly irregular pulse suggests atrial fibrillation, often associated with PAH. In atrial fibrillation, the irregular and rapid contractions lead to ineffective atrial contraction, resulting in absent 'a' waves in the JVP waveform.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Cannon a waves are seen in complete heart block or AV dissociation.</li><li>Option C: Rapid x descent is associated with constrictive pericarditis.</li><li>Option D: Rapid y descent is indicative of constrictive pericarditis.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N344", stem: "A 50-year-old lady presents with SOB and angina pectoris episodes. Work up shows aortic stenosis. Which of the following is the reason behind these chest pain episodes?", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["Increased pressure in aorta", "Decreased pressure in aorta", "Increased oxygen consumption in heart", "Increase in volume overload of heart"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>In aortic stenosis, the narrowed aortic valve obstructs blood flow, increasing left ventricular pressure and leading to hypertrophy. The hypertrophied myocardium increases oxygen demand, but coronary perfusion is compromised (especially during diastole). This imbalance between increased oxygen demand and reduced supply leads to myocardial ischemia and angina.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Pressure increases in the left ventricle, not the aorta.</li><li>Option B: Lower aortic pressure is not the direct cause of angina.</li><li>Option D: Volume overload is associated with mitral regurgitation or heart failure.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N345", stem: "A patient presents with joint swelling, a pan systolic murmur, negative rheumatoid factor (RF), and elevated ESR. What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Acute rheumatic fever", "Seronegative rheumatoid arthritis (RA)", "Juvenile spondyloarthropathy", "Ankylosing spondylitis"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Acute Rheumatic Fever (ARF) commonly presents with migratory arthritis (joint swelling), carditis (pan-systolic murmur suggestive of mitral regurgitation), and elevated ESR. The negative rheumatoid factor helps distinguish it from rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: RA usually involves symmetrical joints and is less likely to cause heart murmurs.</li><li>Option C: Affects spine/sacroiliac joints, not typically presenting with pan-systolic murmur.</li><li>Option D: Primarily affects axial skeleton, not associated with pan-systolic murmur.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N346", stem: "A 35 year patient presents with features of hyperthyroidism, characterized by decreased TSH levels and elevated free T3 and T4. Which of the following statements about this condition is NOT true?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh5dkBIyGxcaH4zFX-HnD9FyXRcML5FF8U_6AbxKcXdCbkYWekAWLo_g5DiWIQddsynaUcQyaePulSRZL65NzcIBIkERMvyIJqATXu9eA0BYVgRrLj6S2D-D4zeJWJvC8W0qySn2r7icdqDMGTI-UlbwqGupaS18VEfqPpOqXq1bWj8i6jmfJ-71GvrvJI/s649/ceea37b2-26a9-47e8-94a9-61d17cca1e48.jpg", ans_key: "A", options: ["The condition will improve simultaneously with improvement in the thyrotoxic state.", "In 10% of cases, the condition is present without hyperthyroidism.", "Severe disease can cause vision loss.", "No specs criteria is used for this condition."], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>This statement is not true because the condition being referred to is likely Graves' ophthalmopathy (thyroid eye disease), which does not always improve simultaneously with the resolution of the thyrotoxic state. The eye manifestations can persist or even worsen independently of the thyroid hormone levels.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Options B, C and D: These are true statements regarding hyperthyroidism and Graves' ophthalmopathy.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N347", stem: "A 40-year-old patient presents with symptoms of anemia, depigmented hair, bleeding gums, and diffuse hair loss. Which of the following mineral deficiencies is most likely associated with this clinical presentation?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Copper", "Iron", "Fluoride", "Zinc"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The clinical presentation of anemia, depigmented hair, bleeding gums, and diffuse hair loss is most consistent with copper deficiency. Copper is vital for iron metabolism (anemia), melanin production (depigmented hair), and collagen synthesis (bleeding gums/hair loss).<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Iron deficiency causes anemia but not depigmented hair or bleeding gums.</li><li>Option C: Fluoride deficiency is linked to dental caries.</li><li>Option D: Zinc deficiency causes hair loss and dermatitis but not depigmented hair or bleeding gums.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N348", stem: "Patient presents with features of right heart failure and exhibits a rapid Y descent on cardiac examination. What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Constrictive pericarditis", "Cardiac tamponade", "Pulmonary hypertension", "Right ventricular infarction"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Constrictive pericarditis leads to impaired filling of the heart due to a thickened pericardium. A rapid Y descent on JVP is a classic finding, reflecting rapid early diastolic filling against the rigid pericardium. Signs of right heart failure like ascites and edema are common.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Cardiac tamponade presents with a blunted or absent Y descent.</li><li>Option C: Pulmonary hypertension JVP findings relate to elevated pressure, not rapid Y descent.</li><li>Option D: Right ventricular infarction typically shows an elevated a-wave or prominent X descent.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N349", stem: "A patient presents with hypotension, hyponatremia, and blackening of the knuckle. Which of the following conditions is most likely associated with these symptoms?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhKq4owqJaRPH_ljDX_kniowQRNQcWR0xx7X5z4enmb_D5X27nvDA9OF3KHfI1TpGX3PBXqU730X-IL3v9DbCIZYgkZHP1CpvKSWw605oOsvqrUvjeUQg8oBp8nOyA9WHIVbHGpnPYEe6YTinVm1T_WhjfBhsT_oDGix6rtEkhVRWHCiXAnS-5lUMgKvKQ/s573/5588b388-38e4-4d76-a914-4c4aa8086131.png", ans_key: "D", options: ["Conn syndrome", "Cushing's syndrome", "Primary ACTH deficiency", "Addison's disease"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Addison's Disease presents with hypotension (low cortisol), hyponatremia (low aldosterone), and hyperpigmentation (increased ACTH stimulating melanocytes), which explains the blackening of the knuckles.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Conn syndrome (hyperaldosteronism) leads to hypertension and hypokalemia.</li><li>Option B: Cushing's syndrome leads to hypertension and hyperglycemia.</li><li>Option C: Primary ACTH deficiency does not cause hyperpigmentation.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N350", stem: "Patient presents with recurrent lung infections and CXR is given below. He is infertile too. What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Kartagener syndrome", "Cystic fibrosis", "DiGeorge syndrome", "Down syndrome"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Kartagener syndrome is characterized by a triad of situs inversus (dextrocardia), chronic sinusitis, and bronchiectasis. The recurrent lung infections and infertility (due to immotile cilia) are consistent with this diagnosis. Dextrocardia on CXR supports it.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Cystic fibrosis causes lung infections and infertility but not dextrocardia.</li><li>Option C: DiGeorge syndrome involves heart defects and immune issues but not dextrocardia/infertility triad.</li><li>Option D: Down syndrome is not specifically associated with this triad.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N351", stem: "A young woman presents with weight loss, tachycardia, heat intolerance, and tremors. On examination, she has exophthalmos. What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["Parkinson's disease", "Graves' disease", "Addison's disease", "Alzheimer's disease"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Graves' disease is an autoimmune disorder leading to hyperthyroidism. Symptoms like weight loss, tachycardia, heat intolerance, and tremors are characteristic. Exophthalmos is a hallmark feature distinguishing it from other conditions.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Parkinson's presents with tremors/rigidity but not hyperthyroid symptoms or exophthalmos.</li><li>Option C: Addison's presents with weight loss but also hypotension and hyperpigmentation, not hyperthyroid signs.</li><li>Option D: Alzheimer's affects memory/cognition.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N352", stem: "What instrument is used to Insert this tube?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhdjX0sZvXtMjN3_NvdmF5khxTOJxJ7QDoPSakxVO6JI0WOJlOb8uW-Qnzciv2mji2f1USBCHyqTgF2fUxYZ4aWERHnDB-HcGGEFKlRk_HJBgD8ZRHM1Nj79e6lgBbZTaWNXTM-d8h7y10h_TwXzu_lvAtlc-UoKdqRo-UPn77-QvSXh-IfopPofwB4ewI/s395/a251df9a-44e4-4d53-8796-fa019bf43722.png", ans_key: "B", options: ["Nephroscope", "Cysto-urethroscope", "Ureteroscope", "Endoscope"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>A Cysto-urethroscope is used to visualize the bladder and urethra, allowing for the insertion of various tubes or instruments for diagnostic or therapeutic purposes in the urinary tract.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Nephroscope is for kidney visualization (e.g., PCNL).</li><li>Option C: Ureteroscope is for ureters.</li><li>Option D: Endoscope is a general term.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N353", stem: "What is the ideal pressure setting for vacuum-assisted closure (VAC) therapy?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["-125 mm Hg", "60 to 80 mm Hg", "130 mm Hg", "80 to 100 mm Hg"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>-125 mm Hg is the most commonly recommended pressure setting for VAC therapy. It promotes wound healing, reduces edema, and enhances blood flow while minimizing tissue damage.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Lower pressure range for sensitive areas.</li><li>Option C: Slightly higher, may increase risk of damage.</li><li>Option D: Not the standard setting.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N354", stem: "A 8-year-old child presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with a complaint of scrotal pain, with a history of trauma 5 hours prior. Upon surgical exploration, the findings suggest significant damage. What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhkUlPndS52FAVzUrPi1QWPUuPlaOyraJA2JG2Y7cXSEhwbpr9upHbf9m-2ODCyCdQ1uYMpCrZABXbdSgocPStZneMPqogLomWVkKSszXrMLoSvBPNzFu_tr_VxIO3SadBZDyBdNGvmrBogVCKpPrdAb9aw96Lpr-aSR4tydtnfjBPVpESDeksTP_LJlQM/s333/652d6745-9f6b-424c-96e1-f10aa6538280.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Testicular torsion with gangrene", "Torsion of testicular appendages with gangrene", "Gangrene", "Hematoma"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Testicular torsion involves twisting of the spermatic cord, cutting off blood supply. If untreated for hours, it leads to ischemia and gangrene. The history of trauma, rapid onset pain, and surgical findings strongly suggest this.<br><br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhbwRaBfCymJ3nOxRpiKhf9MuMfwyh-z6MSkviO1EtQiasDbFuyn50Jw2oOq5qxYayRRwBzPwrB1FbCkzHyGAU3YvSYT2pjL4U7Bo7OG8NcMUHAZJrA669q1gltmMDz9ocT4LZgxUnmDAk6CkNnbKJUwoBmz2AYUdh1r0GmPOMf-ubA-Mwx2fxIkremAy0/s506/dbd259c1-b0d6-485b-9005-245f21395370.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhs9WtXOvMqwdfoQv_oi4xH8gvB8Z7dGmayZWSKR-L7kh5akcDEaGAXHMM8yXFVjaKThyphenhyphen2yYTRQj7813CZz7Yl0p3USLQhVsIQLF1VeldSZQho4qQU119181Wcj7azCZpXwK1Neh_hT13NHysEuJYAl9uwwkfmlMTcQ8URvfY5BLc066uUbvu1_VBDlJ5M/s406/2ada612d-89fe-4af5-ac91-a93341105c11.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Torsion of appendages is less severe and doesn't typically cause extensive gangrene.<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhN8jGvfhCE86IsLTf-DchozTflfr40dX4755pIi9LxewuzJMmPAN9okvCvm-ye-0S0QxurmYeXWYE8gXH6RZIp9OfNJ_-MZnbHwwa3YisqXdJEQuD4GLumkZKJU8wTKngnETMmd4wRppCOxDqONxGhy6CA_AY5gaiIfHOivkSw3xIRqc9urfssRbJgl38/s613/5169b3ec-4ba6-4f1d-ad36-18875adb5562.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /></li><li>Option C: 'Gangrene' is nonspecific without the underlying cause.<br></li><li>Option D: Hematoma causes swelling/pain but not ischemic gangrene unless vascular injury exists.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N355", stem: "A 50 year old patient presents to the outpatient department with an ulcerated breast tumor and liver metastasis. What is the appropriate management?", img: "", ans_key: "D", options: ["Simple mastectomy", "Modified Radical Mastectomy (MRM)", "Radical mastectomy", "Neoadjuvant chemotherapy followed by surgery"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>For stage 4 breast cancer with distant metastases (liver), the primary goal is systemic control. Neoadjuvant chemotherapy is used to downstage the disease and reduce tumor burden. Surgery may be considered later depending on response.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A, B, C: Surgical options like mastectomy are not the primary initial treatment for stage 4 metastatic disease.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N356", stem: "Diagnose the condition based on the image provided.", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiCRYYCNQgQbqAoXa9hhsmpTR6UH9LQFFlb1VU3IyFUD-ukWSIZTzdJzQv-DjArUgSwFyP6gG1mAychhDVdoJHAmHH0Se4VY-svUcUr8Md4_Z4LTfVGUUKx6UHfAq3pRbuOdiW1yztE7ltWLppRk-bJba0WKyDX1BEUb7b3VkGudRdIUvL_iMgu00uRCc0/s630/1000167176.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Renal cyst", "Renal tumor", "ADPKD", "Hydatid cyst"], subject: "Radiology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>A renal cyst will show a unilocular cystic lesion as seen in the image.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Renal tumors are solid masses.</li><li>Option C: ADPKD shows multiple cysts.</li><li>Option D: Hydatid cysts are typically in liver/lungs.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N357", stem: "Identify the stage of disease given in the image.", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/a/AVvXsEgpUce6R0PeDNNh9mgEFRDLh4AmlITeJmyVVYtBWRMIxh9C7cF8WaORXHT7SlU2EvcNtDaQ_TZgF0OPokfQJy1ARgxTPhh8il_fj70CnBBxtnOYlDGRc6jsm4EIpk-40Fw0dM0cAD8NnDny_RVxWnu_Qg6w0QTALQHNLjHqTOmyYsmbRgbGHhovdzxwv6A", ans_key: "A", options: ["Type 1", "Type 2", "Type 3", "Type 4"], subject: "Radiology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The image describes a cyst that becomes more complex, often with daughter cysts, membranes, or debris (Mixed pattern with 'water lily sign' or internal debris). This corresponds to CE3 (Transitional) in WHO classification, often referred to as Type 3 in other classifications where the cyst begins to mature/degenerate.<br>(Note: The provided solution text maps the description 'Cyst with detached membranes' to CE3 A / Type II in Gharbi. However, the question asks to identify the stage from the image which seems to show a complex cyst. Based on the options and standard staging, Type 3 (Gharbi) is a multiseptated/honeycomb cyst. Type 2 is detached membrane. The answer key says 'Correct Answer' with no letter, but based on the description of 'daughter cysts' and 'water lily sign', it aligns with transitional stages.)<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Type 1: Unilocular anechoic.</li><li>Type 4: Heterogenous, inactive.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N358", stem: "Endoscopic image shows the following finding. What is the diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiLDCXwK3_r5C2H8Qe7EQ-cRcgsx_VauGDDOhTDr4fEgSGLAXdmrcbZgkurx1264cBxEB1kRtekNLeC08qlISHVfW1_Y7iCGEEsMBM3bRCZ0S_j_VmvxCs1RV6qAYaUUOvskkPDqb10-Ne2wzLUvjOUNHPF6CJRJFXW1rDHJo0UXeyBPIxfiFMi9wvtdkg/s689/144471d4-03da-4e38-a223-b7dff34f47d3.png", ans_key: "B", options: ["Barrett's esophagus", "Esophageal varices", "Gastric erosion", "Chronic GERD"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Esophageal varices are dilated submucosal veins in the esophagus, seen in portal hypertension. Endoscopically, they appear as prominent, tortuous veins along the esophageal wall.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Barrett's shows salmon-colored mucosa.</li><li>Option C: Gastric erosions are ulcers/red areas in the stomach.</li><li>Option D: GERD causes mucosal changes but not dilated veins.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N359", stem: "A 24 year old patient presents with an umbilical hernia that was previously reducible but has now become Irreducible. Which of the following is the most appropriate management option?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhapmqz9XQHMZv4smTOqSuQ8ofMmsPSXzLSabZFuu5lSb4wgsCENydZG6HoE5EUNWbY2iklDduE3hP6S3DLBjplabxC9ajCMjW5_yryigTR4WyFvqqS5o8R-0zsiZK_nl91xNLNoqQq7WZcRKWf5udQH6RgVJNABp_aTonOWD_54970iYWHn3qoBgfB26w/s463/721cd64e-5ad9-4986-96dd-ff9b074740db.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Umbilical excision", "Umbilical excision with mesh hernioplasty", "Mesh hernioplasty", "Conservative management"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>For an irreducible hernia, there is a risk of strangulation. Surgical intervention with umbilical excision (Mayo's repair) is appropriate. Mesh hernioplasty is generally contraindicated in strangulated/irreducible cases due to infection risk.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B & C: Mesh is contraindicated in strangulation/potential contamination.</li><li>Option D: Conservative management is not appropriate for irreducible hernia.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N360", stem: "A 43-year-old female presents with an irregular 5 x 6 cm mass in the right breast. Histopathological examination reveals findings consistent with which of the following diagnoses?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg-XW0sOLUd-K6bMLZoIhOto30leQC-HY1dhoYzLZrry5yFvqRZmE3wgDyWG4txy-CfWV7enOX3EIosUpZloV8197m8fqwNPjrWpfph6IQeQFXuHMGBb68dWAWSRZq27DKcvsm5CxkIgussOd7u3UT48eJUTb5hVUf1g7bDZHWEuhBT3j3c0DdwYM7fBQE/s2048/e01f1dd2-8660-4580-a082-8371ed749b1b.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Phyllodes tumor", "Fibroadenoma", "Mastitis", "Grade 2 breast tumor"], subject: "Pathology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Phyllodes tumor is a rare fibroepithelial tumor characterized by a leaf-like pattern on histopathology with stromal overgrowth. The description of a large irregular mass in a middle-aged woman aligns with this diagnosis.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Fibroadenoma lacks stromal overgrowth and is usually well-circumscribed in younger women.</li><li>Option C: Mastitis is inflammatory.</li><li>Option D: Grade 2 tumor refers to invasive carcinoma, not the leaf-like pattern described.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N361", stem: "What type of dressing is used to cover this post-burn wound?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgOUt4spNPG_CVgK1Slgfa8gJboWDsf6KiwLE6HKhZIFv9SslmkBm-kd4muU0G7m7Kvir56jBXA8HR8K4gJ0kqfVxqpjkrbf-9jIQQT_uYkbgxuFJBOlf3uKY8Vii1B8m7Nl7ddoObBwq_0XgXznC-BI0AVi026O1dowB45SgqUr2VqimXRL-76bAdJHis/s1200/1d7db522-6f5e-472b-88ae-ca6f301a72a6.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Split thickness skin graft", "Full thickness skin graft", "VAC dressing", "Normal saline dressing"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>A split-thickness skin graft (STSG) involves transplanting the top layers of skin to cover a post-burn wound. It is the primary coverage method.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Full thickness is for smaller, cosmetic wounds.</li><li>Option C: VAC is for healing complex wounds, not covering grafts.</li><li>Option D: Secondary coverage.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N362", stem: "A 35 year old truck driver presented with pain in the gluteal region along with swelling. What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEi3OLmxgfPf8lEGfixm5O0b-rSRT3ecuEFAd335uX1ziprtYaUHsEiPL-gO7qulRXhnsNZxhygMx_iHFsxbacOO-N39yO1qSxMB9H3vIe_k0_YIwHM5v8Cxv1-1NLoqFyV-tOMt7faXBVZ4x2wPHAQXasg90iKAvniCtL8b09gugpNyqmlPE_WHWuDSJBY/s440/7b61da69-d397-4e4b-b20c-f28032c27aad.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Pilonidal sinus", "Fistula in ano", "Fissure in ano", "Gluteal abscess"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Pilonidal sinus occurs near the sacrococcygeal area, often in people who sit for prolonged periods (like truck drivers). It causes pain, swelling, and abscess formation in the gluteal cleft.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Fistula in ano causes perianal symptoms.</li><li>Option C: Fissure causes pain during defecation.</li><li>Option D: Gluteal abscess is nonspecific; pilonidal is more specific to the history.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N363", stem: "A child presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with a radiological image as given. What is the most appropriate management for this condition?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg1R48jX2JYw07ujVSLKqTN3hcCqWoRCMeb7RbsKDrTtYetlK0xbCGAZCaL7EfvlRsDzoCgcPYn_IP2TqbIvM1eDGEVXYcfGecR3mobxyVV9V9qMQWYkTkrpoIMrLs1kalMERYqOJNh_vbB1GoUlEhf6yBvoGHOySDs5NHMlt0ubP3-IOUT6NwtLiqLPc8/s630/ae72ced3-12ca-4a4a-8872-5f44fe39d76e.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Endoscopic ablation", "Dilation of urethra", "Dilation of urethra and bladder", "Conservative"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The image (MCU showing Posterior Urethral Valves) requires endoscopic ablation (fulguration) of the valves to relieve obstruction.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B & C: Dilation is not the standard treatment for valves.</li><li>Option D: Conservative management does not resolve obstruction.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N364", stem: "Identify the grade of the condition given in the image below?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh5ou886MOJo_BSMDIXZGOejNk-1KTUWXOktZnLvDPM07ErkcfcYxy91IsAZKdYEFnFua3h5UNfEh_q9wwBBIykY4Z7EAP6QCa1AKJjCLFx5ho1xi5bqiTfDU_f-3lUW-QfD1foSvDvADPelto_gj80HOp6W2Dpkokimrb6QpIRDhL_v02WDhUn04gDoFk/s560/b36fa317-45fd-41b5-b804-c4f2b1369dd8.png", ans_key: "D", options: ["Grade 1", "Grade 2", "Grade 3", "Grade 4"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The image shows a deep ulcer with exposed bone, muscle, or tendon, characteristic of a Grade 4 pressure sore.<br<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiJdAfWeRcgOe_hyphenhyphentpitpLLdcPnZG6wIY2G02jCtIOhAloiJDqvmGZlaQbfojpT3A6h2VbsgNDxRovopm_eQce0xk19-tPLJij5G4k8u-nt27u0ZgtsOoJR-6Gbr59LSqNjxfNt44Kihe6-hgJRJVd_YdkhmT24jG71h0aCu6uZRr-qro-NgyCuRUxKS4w/s610/1359c3ba-39a0-4adf-999a-e4e1d3101a09.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br>><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Grade 1: Erythema only.<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhJ8zI6l1BWjUPnj0mYoM_4OkrydULJTQnoKU6aW_130mHr22LfW5Al10eNWiMpsR3hc9HIf2IXyYLnVhEFHIkwe7cpGvE-5wZtbaUj8T5nzqGW6lT3LUA6QZcVtmz5H6kHisIoUTxgAxwDmAAjsbksG9BqaN2yFbH1VHU5OZkCJpqt84QtSAGeu2-lQ3o/s611/b194b5f3-850a-4233-96d1-c3b846fa404f.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br></li><li>Grade 2: Partial thickness skin loss.<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjWdYFs73NsvAyBFAZb7JQCbjLt-YVn3To_hcdB5JqxdOwL5El498QLUZwIAYgVAbg2R9wH9LSc4hr6ixEt8TBvy7K3fqtU2MQ8F2vbfiwIVJy1ySKFfqAV9XW0v_qo-myypVEDKVVGblZnE6oQCZfb-NX42Ap2uKs-MSWPWCHaVc2b71cqsEX7N0c4qJk/s609/74a93e1f-fa3d-4818-a238-42ee328c9c19.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br></li><li>Grade 3: Full thickness loss but bone/muscle not exposed.<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEibfemuB5Tk2z714IxsBVLVJvy0Ghg7p5zzQFLSYkrNjMG9djeBg0Rt0yVKTb-Ghu1eXUtVGrEqkJVA93g0e9_z1_VqT_la0muCxXsjsWyDTzR9GSwI2ly6UM7F30oiNdb9LGQJnxeoOazdXyTRRh0ZSdHzskEdok3w4wveiyFqGBKNtpn77LKA_TTX1Tw/s612/01a6d256-f127-44ef-98a8-cab94d88f416.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br></li></ul>" },
{ q: "N365", stem: "Which of the following is an indication for adjuvant radiotherapy in oral malignancy after resection and modified radical neck dissection (MRND)?", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["Extranodal extension", "Multiple lymph node metastasis", "T3 tumor", "Close margin"], subject: "ENT", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Multiple lymph node metastases (particularly three or more) significantly increase recurrence risk, indicating adjuvant radiotherapy. (Note: Extranodal extension is also a strong indication, often for chemoradiation. However, multiple nodes is a standard indication for RT).<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: ENE often warrants concurrent chemoradiotherapy.</li><li>Option C: T3 alone may not be as definitive as nodal status.</li><li>Option D: Close margins are a relative indication.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N366", stem: "A young patient presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with recurrent colicky abdominal pain. Urine examination reveals the presence of red blood cells (RBCs). What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh9Vg8qD9zxKD54DGIveBCK6dX9GxNc2wuqDrXEilUC4X8ItxiSB9CB7NTHm40yM6x2xlygV-EpiUw-A1kdYRww5b-Umqs39m8B3YYh1j1BDXZ3xK6m8KVfjCFLg5_P_BCpmamBWdup5MV0Haxyf_yGDe7e8Sgf1b4NVakVkMYC4zTjFXC4JmsNdnRfSvY/s431/29bfe618-8594-41d5-8fa4-d04630dfd721.png", ans_key: "D", options: ["Glomerulonephritis", "Oxalate stone", "Polycystic kidney disease", "Cystine stone"], subject: "Medicine", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The presence of benzene-shaped (hexagonal) crystals in the urine (implied by the solution, though not explicitly in stem, 'benzene' shape is key for Cystine) along with RBCs suggests cystinuria leading to cystine stones.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: GN presents with casts/proteinuria.</li><li>Option B: Oxalate stones have envelope-shaped crystals.</li><li>Option C: PKD causes cysts/hematuria but not hexagonal crystals.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N367", stem: "A 28 year old man presents to the emergency room with back pain following a road traffic accident. There was no history of neurological deficit and the patient is stable now. X ray spine is done. What is the diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgTt0xgantUo2wSyDkgK3TtDonyMhGzuDxWVitLqvxBHpF-BzvA7n2_GSk1GU_uA4Sa9cS67k8rsu47SjUubH29PcHaMeLbIvf0OHAMVu_u-rrqYS8-9y1psJAeUyYlsz-TtnlT6MeLzziGZHe3yNNP1rrCNQd-sUyGcu4yFkaZcCn1s9Om2UwGJpwT-Mc/s844/88134003-550a-407d-a913-012a5eec1fd5.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Spinous process fracture", "Chance fracture", "Fracture of base of vertebrae", "Compressed fracture"], subject: "Orthopedics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>A spinous process fracture (Clay Shoveler's is a type, but here likely traumatic) occurs due to hyperextension or direct trauma. X-rays show a fracture of the spinous process while the body remains intact.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Chance fracture involves vertebral body.</li><li>Option D: Compression fracture shows loss of vertebral height.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N368", stem: "A 10 year old male child presents with growth failure. Biochemical analysis shows normal Calcium, normal PTH, reduced phosphate, and increased ALP. What is the diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEi2XyDQzTSdtUkmxagTYa9OLb7M7MfZvm0es5weLkrCiZAvZFjx6kQKTFzuyg9zAQqM7DVkEpjkK-c2NQjuJjxTGCx3bLY8X4mvaJi03hdKZhyphenhyphenQ9wVwoYQTnXk36oM_6rBTFbSTVEVvy4WlCAX5McXlwyLa2PbC7PHH1ggqKpmjjOMIZAlXT0e9isnaAwQ/s1280/f8020f2c-5165-42ba-a9fa-5c1fe813ff28.png", ans_key: "B", options: ["Nutritional rickets", "Hypophosphatemic rickets", "Type 1 VDDR", "Type 2 VDDR"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Hypophosphatemic rickets is characterized by low phosphate, high ALP, normal calcium, and normal PTH (due to renal phosphate wasting).<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Nutritional rickets has low Ca, high PTH.</li><li>Option C: Type 1 VDDR has low Ca, high PTH.</li><li>Option D: Type 2 VDDR has high PTH, high ALP.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N369", stem: "A 20 year old male football player had a twist in the ankle and knee. Clinically, no bony injury was appreciated. The examiner is performing a test to assess the knee joint. Which test is this?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjY2Fa-0yOeveUGePCHuWFrpbGHbjdPRNwQsihUykhyphenhyphenwpGXgnRuOe3MkPQ1HMfOzCnuwrgNpjU4IoOjOyFoaahFH5wqJ0Qdrls5Ib2T3C2_LCyf_QGYV3b89NlxcCSQ1oCEyZ7dQ8V5AqJAaphgTjGOf-8XrtDxskCZucmtzkXpcYt88lR99bYROUF2IBI/s640/7ecc850f-5dc8-4f85-9a02-d5cdc6f4ec8d.png", ans_key: "C", options: ["Posterior drawer for PCL", "McMurray", "Lachman", "Anterior drawer for ACL"], subject: "Orthopedics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The Lachman test assesses the ACL. With the knee flexed at 20-30 degrees, the tibia is pulled forward. It is the most sensitive test for ACL injury.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Posterior drawer is for PCL.</li><li>Option B: McMurray is for meniscus.</li><li>Option D: Anterior drawer is at 90 degrees flexion.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N370", stem: "A heavy lifter presents with lower back ache. Identify the nerve compressed in the following disc prolapse?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhbZX14t5bkPLtcAr0QUM28YbXtpIxGWUErEJsKD46SFDls6kwdXObwWD67fjvEUyfEopd9iK6pgrnZhnAICiza8L1dr8Me0IPHZ6HdlAmUClmXr29pptzFlxQtHqo6qwhukgxLIc5zGnGZ6OpTafnEv5OvPn_V31MMWRjv0pBEt_hAumV_z1rm2aYV7aw/s490/fd2a956a-6573-451f-981c-095e4e66b755.jpg", ans_key: "B", options: ["L4", "L5", "L3", "S4"], subject: "Orthopedics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The L5 nerve root is most commonly affected in disc prolapse (e.g., L4-L5 disc herniation compresses L5). Symptoms include pain radiating down the leg and weakness in dorsiflexion.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: L4 affects anterior thigh/knee.</li><li>Option C: S1 affects posterior leg/plantar flexion.</li><li>Option D: S4 affects perineum.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N371", stem: "A 10-year-old male child presents with fever and tenderness in the left lower limb for a few days. The limb is warm to the touch and ESR is raised. An X-ray reveals periosteal elevation. What is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhXRGGI6SasJEuW4_otKgy-4gzPPFzGB1FSa3H4cBcbES92ND8_bAnl6_AY65GoO-a5m3b8lsjPJbnomdocDDbDF0BPWrseoVJgD2rD19iLWuS3XwYE0lT5gBq9T86nAYI_VcCrKMBNJFWoRE_45yAv9en_m-VWRGelDcKMHgqhKv6d2VQFGEiVpgfHeq8/s630/684faf0f-d00f-4f78-bb24-81c08ae88876.png", ans_key: "C", options: ["Ewing sarcoma", "Osteosarcoma", "Osteomyelitis", "Giant Cell Tumor (GCT)"], subject: "Orthopedics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Osteomyelitis is an infection presenting with fever, localized pain/warmth, and raised ESR. Periosteal elevation is seen on X-ray. The acute inflammatory signs favor infection over tumor.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Ewing's has onion-skin appearance.</li><li>Option B: Osteosarcoma has sunburst pattern.</li><li>Option D: GCT is lytic, eccentric.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N372", stem: "A young man experienced the following fracture. Identify the classification and stage of the fracture?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEi0zjJ830b_N4nUz-Lpeau5a4-8D-JSfCEbY0SMzZGCESzzuYKi5oS53OVPRMqJWK9Ai9d6RhpLakYSX02tz3DldaJTkdFwjYjcwscXaLJGkRSi5Sq41R3iHZ0iDCEQzgAC46Vyt8zcGzVePemo7D9ph5H6YKD9VpVplKaYDZerdcpYRfENAAF_x2dYbmI/s850/e091171b-81c5-4f2b-bede-946d5e34ab25.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Gartland 3", "Gartland 2", "Salter Harris 3", "Salter Harris 2"], subject: "Orthopedics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Gartland classification is for supracondylar humerus fractures. Gartland Type 3 is completely displaced with no cortical contact, which is unstable.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Gartland 2 is partial displacement with intact posterior cortex.</li><li>Option C & D: Salter-Harris is for growth plate fractures.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N373", stem: "Identify the orthopedic implant shown in the image.", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhHYmxY3GmZrYnZyRLOUjbc2_ztQuGNqyhvNlY-XCmyNQI6XGHWPP4S8EIqYG4nPiPJybq-6A0T1gEZwlzxnmoqQ37eFnEiVfJDHWBxTwKFVDA9cNY0Ve9FWApUQrBUcs_kihC9q9tNfT2mOzD8F14rYlPlVVskomPmiccWIEd9plbcxsnvr3qoaNtBueM/s594/09aec2c1-7f3b-4f52-9204-a55aaf0ede0b.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Dynamic hip screw", "Adynamic hip screw", "Condylar hip screw", "Intramedullary nail"], subject: "Orthopedics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) is used for intertrochanteric fractures. It has a large lag screw and a side plate, allowing controlled collapse.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Incorrect term.</li><li>Option C: For distal femur.</li><li>Option D: Intramedullary nail is a rod.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N374", stem: "A 30 year old male patient presents with a 5th metatarsal fracture. For how many days he/she would have to wear a cast?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjXUmQ4rIA_5Ci5q-TTKoupDoLjDZAoUu87eZftGFUka6c9blZiWTIrqFNUdanNzFoSNWoDViQP9dnfU173wQx7jHET_HCzLuWHmta6uHVWY14p4k7o-eLVAGzAuBs_lxNWyMZuDoIahfnra8hPSezPmnoYgUfb9UXjd_6k2cx0D4CRzWPV1muv8I9g4yU/s1146/f04fd4f5-666b-41ce-87e0-fd4fd9b6ab95.png", ans_key: "C", options: ["2-3 weeks", "3-5 weeks", "6-8 weeks", "16-20 weeks"], subject: "Orthopedics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>6-8 weeks is the typical duration for casting a 5th metatarsal fracture (e.g., Jones fracture) to allow adequate healing.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Options A, B, and D are incorrect durations.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N375", stem: "An infant presents with vomiting after feeding. Benedict's test was positive for a non-glucose substance. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Galactosemia due to GAL-P uridyl transferase enzyme deficiency", "Hereditary fructose intolerance due to aldolase B deficiency", "Glucose-6-Phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency", "Galactosemia due to galactokinase enzyme deficiency"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Classic Galactosemia (GALT deficiency) presents with vomiting, jaundice, and failure to thrive after milk feeding. Positive Benedict's test (detects reducing sugars like galactose) with negative glucose oxidase test (specific for glucose) confirms non-glucose reducing sugar (galactose).<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Fructose intolerance presents after fruit/juice introduction, not milk.</li><li>Option C: G6PD causes hemolysis, not positive Benedict's.</li><li>Option D: Galactokinase deficiency causes cataracts, usually not severe systemic symptoms.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N376", stem: "A neonate is found to have the following anomaly upon physical examinations. Which neonatal anomaly is depicted in the image?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhelEUpnX5L-WdyyQQWoV-3M3ZL0Xn_NjinQlhVhrw_H3T_vogjythihRCImvB8iljHcRi_nJ4PSl9lyBnCSJSpTQLlYbMcbW8z_y0NuzHJ6xo-UkZZkgfNa20i_MWlQCDNXSXiz9Vhnkoirdn263NoeoKbTRQfGN40-85paLXMthnJKLg953Mv7pTQC-w/s1200/7ce17654-79a2-42f9-9d71-9caa1691980e.png", ans_key: "D", options: ["Omphalocele", "Gastroschisis", "Patent vitello intestinal duct", "Exstrophy bladder"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Exstrophy bladder is characterized by the exposure of the bladder outside the body due to a lower abdominal wall defect. The bladder mucosa is visible.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Omphalocele is covered by a sac.</li><li>Option B: Gastroschisis is bowel herniation without a sac.</li><li>Option C: PVID involves umbilical discharge/connection.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N377", stem: "A 6-year-old unimmunized child presents to the OPD with a fully Immunized 2-year-old sibling. Upon Inspection, a white membranous layer is observed in the throat of the 6-year-old. What is the next step in management for the contact?", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["Diphtheria toxoid bolus", "Diphtheria toxin", "Penicillin", "No treatment is needed"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>For diphtheria, unimmunized contacts should receive antibiotic prophylaxis (Penicillin or Erythromycin) to prevent infection and spread. (Note: The symptomatic child needs antitoxin and antibiotics; contacts need prophylaxis and immunization update).<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Toxoid is for immunity, not immediate management of exposure/symptoms (though they should be immunized).</li><li>Option B: Toxin is the cause.</li><li>Option D: Prophylaxis is needed.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N378", stem: "A 8 year old male child presented with anemia, mental retardation, bone pains, and hepatosplenomegaly. Bone marrow biopsy showed a 'crumpled tissue paper' appearance. What is the enzyme deficiency producing this condition?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiHBppLht74I3Mmg413DQH8StH5srM8ZNC_Jj5sXWub1JGBgXnP5OMShyV7fuWUmNzebnU8vgw2vwZk4tTxLrhVZZIVFGFZ-3cLVqbkaOBFbB5miAbqEEIRHaaFZ1V-jb1HjuHJCh9K3IS2ekhknZyuoVTEEGScBWq-5_OVlH-UBalO03hzCEaFj80v1Ig/s850/67ceb9fe-46e7-4e15-a488-cc12a1d5c6f7.png", ans_key: "D", options: ["Hexosaminidase-A", "Iduronate 2-sulphatase", "Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase", "Glucocerebrosidase"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Gaucher disease is caused by Glucocerebrosidase deficiency. It presents with hepatosplenomegaly, bone pain, and 'crumpled tissue paper' cells (Gaucher cells) in bone marrow.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Tay-Sachs (Hexosaminidase A) has cherry red spot, no organomegaly.</li><li>Option B: Hunter syndrome (MPS II).</li><li>Option C: G6PD causes hemolysis.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N379", stem: "A 3-year-old male child presents with stable vitals but an ECG showing paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia (PSVT). Which of the following is the appropriate treatment?", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["Cardioversion", "Adenosine 0.2 mg/kg", "Adenosine 0.1 mg/kg", "IV Adrenaline"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>For stable PSVT, the initial pharmacological treatment is Adenosine at 0.1 mg/kg.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Cardioversion is for unstable patients.</li><li>Option B: 0.2 mg/kg is the subsequent dose if the first fails.</li><li>Option D: Adrenaline is for cardiac arrest.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N380", stem: "What is the defect in Celiac Sprue in a child?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Anti-tissue transglutaminase (tTG) antibodies are positive and used as a screening test", "A type of food allergy causing skin rashes", "A genetic disorder leading to lactose intolerance", "An Infection in the gastrointestinal tract caused by bacteria"], subject: "Pediatrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Celiac disease is an autoimmune disorder triggered by gluten. Anti-tissue transglutaminase (tTG) antibodies are the specific screening test.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: It is not a classic IgE food allergy.</li><li>Option C: Not directly lactose intolerance.</li><li>Option D: Not a bacterial infection.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N381", stem: "What is the appropriate age for surgery performed for cleft lip?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["3 months", "6 months", "1 year", "18 months"], subject: "Surgery", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Cleft lip repair is typically performed around 3 months of age (following the Rule of 10s: 10 weeks, 10 lbs, 10 g/dL Hb).<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B & C: Cleft palate is repaired later (6-12 months).</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N382", stem: "A 25 year old woman with full term pregnancy has gone into labor. The flexion point in a ventouse delivery is located at which of the following positions on the fetal head?", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["3 cm posterior to the anterior fontanelle", "3 cm anterior to the posterior fontanelle", "6 cm anterior to the posterior fontanelle", "Midway between the anterior and posterior fontanelle"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The flexion point for ventouse application is located 3 cm anterior to the posterior fontanelle along the sagittal suture. This promotes flexion of the head.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Options A, C, D are incorrect anatomical landmarks for the flexion point.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N383", stem: "Identify the instrument shown below:", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEj2zlhDO7HCVIs_FD5Pa0juCJrB7Anl_XxiPo190NPSQN_JzaU0JSvTsFKRCUYjJxm2x8kbzitmkrDXOvMFfC9a7qq6d4ryT4bY3b8dhHVwC8RR7XVG4UcRW3W0OFW1k0vE6xl9koIam7gWVRnhBmzIp5lfrXHmw3bTbC8n2HCP4JHFjTHBliIFUBU4kSA/s400/4508ab2f-2fc5-4fb6-9978-0c3e3df963a5.png", ans_key: "C", options: ["Kielland", "Wrigley", "Pipers", "None of the above"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Pipers Forceps are specifically designed for the delivery of the after-coming head in breech presentations. They are characterized by a reverse pelvic curve, allowing safe application to the head during breech delivery, which is crucial for avoiding injury to the baby's head and neck.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Kielland forceps are designed with a sliding lock and minimal pelvic curve, often used for rotational deliveries in cases of fetal malposition.</li><li>Option B: Wrigley forceps are smaller, lighter forceps primarily used for low-forceps deliveries or during cesarean sections to assist in delivering the baby's head.<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhm_I0nW7segVEJ_LOHJ8Q0Smvo5qA5eal7r9-3K9K-FwIo6vz_6S4KDsy6Sys9di5Xz0ut_dI9_I3VaZPWjQf_RDHYG9ydTynlqJ5XGLg6mjC_0vgxQh1CH6ciCqJhHkZFNgdNqIeIYkU1C5isJQ6XyGT-Dq6ul2FPO8S1MyywWAYmAU2OmCHWG4IVwnI/s474/0fee6567-2533-4ea3-9af9-0692b2046eff.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br></li></ul>" },
{ q: "N384", stem: "Which of the following is the anticoagulation of choice for a pregnant female at late pregnancy?", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["Warfarin", "Heparin", "Apixaban", "Enoxaparin"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Heparin, specifically unfractionated heparin (UFH), is the anticoagulant of choice in late pregnancy (at/more than 36 weeks). Heparin does not cross the placenta, making it safe for the fetus. In the final weeks of pregnancy, UFH is preferred over low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) like enoxaparin because it has a shorter half-life and can be quickly reversed if needed during labor or in case of delivery.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Warfarin is contraindicated during pregnancy, especially in the third trimester, due to risks of fetal bleeding and teratogenicity.</li><li>Option C: Apixaban is not recommended due to limited safety data.</li><li>Option D: Enoxaparin is safe for most of pregnancy but is switched to UFH near delivery for easier reversal.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N385", stem: "A pregnant female at 37 weeks of gestation presents for a routine antenatal checkup. She is currently on warfarin. What would be the next step?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Switch to LMWH", "Immediate Induction", "LSCS (Lower Segment Caesarean Section)", "Continue the same"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Warfarin is contraindicated in the later stages of pregnancy due to the risk of fetal complications and bleeding during delivery. Low Molecular Weight Heparin (LMWH) is safer for use in pregnancy as it does not cross the placenta. At 37 weeks, switching from warfarin to LMWH is the recommended step to ensure safety during the upcoming delivery.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Induction without managing anticoagulation poses bleeding risks.</li><li>Option C: LSCS requires planning and anticoagulation management beforehand.</li><li>Option D: Continuing warfarin puts the fetus and mother at risk of bleeding complications.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N386", stem: "What is the likely diagnosis for a G2P1L1 woman with a history of hysterectomy?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgvrC3OXf-EmVT6TY4ipJq4TX-GfOCPHK3bokRYTg7AfuNIImrWlUOG66web6NDLJ2yPeNw0Mdf-ylHCa7twzS2n4vS89NkVWgIIfBuqGzSLM2aMb6lHj5mKPHh6RCy7rl6SKNHRgU3txDzMSUju136DRNpiWk4yWm33bIKLriNfQEUioDrUV4sfRU1iaA/s1280/cab6a70a-28f2-42a1-87b3-3869eca21ba8.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Placenta accreta", "Placenta Inversion", "Placenta abruption", "Placenta previa"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Placenta accreta is a condition where the placenta attaches too deeply to the uterine wall. In women who have undergone a hysterectomy (likely partial or with retained tissue/cervical stump pregnancy contexts or previous scars), abnormal attachment can occur. The image typically shows the placenta invading the myometrium.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Placenta inversion is a complication of delivery (uterine inversion), not typically described this way.</li><li>Option C: Abruption is premature separation, not abnormal attachment.</li><li>Option D: Placenta previa involves covering the cervix, not necessarily invasion.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N387", stem: "A 27 year old pregnant woman diagnosed with impending eclampsia is started on the Pritchard regimen for magnesium sulfate administration. Under which of the following conditions should the treatment be stopped?", img: "", ans_key: "D", options: ["Respiratory rate (RR) < 18 breaths per minute", "Visual disturbances start", "Knee Jerk reflex is present", "Urine output less than 60 ml in 4 hours"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Low urine output (less than 100 ml in 4 hours, or specifically < 25-30 ml/hr) indicates potential renal impairment. Since magnesium is excreted by the kidneys, oliguria can lead to accumulation and toxicity. Therefore, a urine output of less than 60 ml in 4 hours is a strict indication to stop the regimen.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Treatment is stopped if RR < 12-16 (depending on guidelines), but < 18 is generally considered safe.</li><li>Option B: Visual disturbances are a sign of worsening preeclampsia, not Mg toxicity.</li><li>Option C: The presence of the knee jerk reflex is a sign of safety; its *absence* would require stopping treatment.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N388", stem: "Identify the type of uterus shown in the image.", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgNWqHo2wWGHQL2RgXsx1PkI78G3M23FUlO7385KkIxGdPW3zwrfjupG68x-r_1C1pe1RHQuE6_omUgge_tUxh9l3auCPd7Qrh9iS9XkAsubPDwmJlyOzKZ6VepHdCzHT_DvPqNp5bYfB2tijihoznoyLPpGZ3cph8njfKbzlR3Vhc3pZ9nlOGuKZ6tdMQ/s660/01bab151-2cc6-4988-b7c3-0bdbc1b68e20.png", ans_key: "B", options: ["Bicornuate", "Didelphys", "Arcuate", "Aseptate"], subject: "Gynecology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>The Didelphys Uterus involves two completely separate uterine cavities, often with dual cervices and sometimes two vaginas. The image shows distinct, separate uterine structures.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Bicornuate uterus has a deep fundal indentation and a heart shape but partial fusion at the bottom.</li><li>Option C: Arcuate uterus has a mild fundal indentation.</li><li>Option D: Aseptate (or septate) has a normal external contour but an internal septum.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N389", stem: "A patient presents with a new 2.3 cm black nodular mass near an episiotomy scar that is painful and expands during menstruation. What is the most likely cause?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Endometriosis", "Melanoma", "Foreign body granuloma", "Inclusion cyst"], subject: "Gynecology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Scar endometriosis is characterized by the presence of endometrial tissue in a surgical scar (like an episiotomy). It presents as a painful, palpable mass that often swells and becomes more painful during menstruation due to hormonal response.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Melanoma is a malignancy and would not show cyclic pain.</li><li>Option C: Granuloma is a reaction to foreign material, non-cyclic.</li><li>Option D: Inclusion cyst is usually painless and non-cyclic.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N390", stem: "Which of the following is the tumor marker for ovarian solid cystic mass in a 25-year-old female?", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["Ca125, AFP, HCG, CEA", "Ca125, AFP, HCG, Ca 19.9", "Ca125, AFP, HCG, LDH", "Ca125, AFP, HCG, Ca 15.3"], subject: "Gynecology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>In a young female (25 years old), germ cell tumors are more common than epithelial tumors. The relevant markers include AFP (Yolk sac tumor), HCG (Choriocarcinoma), and LDH (Dysgerminoma). CA-125 is also checked to rule out epithelial components or other pathologies.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Options A, B, and D include markers like CEA, Ca 19.9, and Ca 15.3 which are more relevant for mucinous, GI, or breast malignancies.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N391", stem: "Identify the maneuver shown in the Image", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh8x67G6L_KDlxQL9p9NYkyVBdxVQ0GXEhSXtBZSQttkYXBBzpPQZ6DdN5FznQDSPEbjCt9Z5dcjkJPegpi0O0L7Rlz1A9YHD83yw5eZPV2gdLZoL4iMqrFLN1zYsgDRLX-p9rfZrNSB1VlAZX0OKYlhgnrvsWW0glohJpJTkGGqXyYnWail5EZPXJz_Ao/s744/2030a470-e45a-478a-90ca-e8e5c32ba0ad.png", ans_key: "A", options: ["Burn-Marshall Maneuver", "Lovset Maneuver", "Mauriceau-Smellie-Veit Maneuver", "None of the above"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br> The Burn-Marshall Maneuver (often referred to as the Burns maneuver) is used to deliver the aftercoming head in a breech delivery. The baby is allowed to hang until the nape of the neck is visible. Gentle upward traction is applied to the fetal body to deliver the head.<br> However, in the context of delivering the shoulders, the term may be incorrectly used; the correct term would generally be Lovset Maneuver.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Lovset maneuver is for the delivery of the arms/shoulders.<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjpTakIMndf4sCs6aMcaONoJ9JBEaSc2AIn-qrOzvyO44YatmHe4oYvWIL0gJN7fRKqHlJJepiGryyl4L8o678-7VWq9lOwyxLIpgLvkPjkNpasetqDmup5k5oOSrMW1j0fStuaoWLqPT0fpsFxtRxasOzzKLXg7jpZ2rPDJys2EUtT5p6j8VV0aRiyab4/s403/475ffb49-c840-4c0c-a6ba-388db03e3ddd.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br></li><li>Option C: Mauriceau-Smellie-Veit Maneuver.<br>This maneuver is used to assist the delivery of the head in a breech presentation. The fetal body is supported on the physician's arm, and fingers are placed in the fetal mouth to provide flexion of the head while applying gentle pressure on the occiput.<br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgK76TJu9_pAhM8sZo4P-_hbunlXhNt7QnEj892jcWN0K0l7FEFQzzoJWDZwFvkoiXZuv1I9YKOMOOv5J9jo7c0vs_EEiWa7XQJYs38EUt4vnp1-cCeBBwKG9xE6ac0v1BXu9WMjFM36A32V_lKvLXgLldgODA7yTyDYiidCK6uz2ccjKTrY9WMY6tMEYk/s403/93d4ed7c-897d-4660-8f74-db60650765fc.png' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br></li></ul>" },
{ q: "N392", stem: "A pregnant woman presents with a history suggestive of hyperthyroidism at 7 weeks of gestation (POG). What is the drug of choice?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Propylthiouracil (PTU)", "Methimazole", "Carbimazole", "Propranolol"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Propylthiouracil (PTU) is the drug of choice for hyperthyroidism in the first trimester of pregnancy because Methimazole/Carbimazole are associated with embryopathy (e.g., Aplasia Cutis). After the first trimester, treatment is often switched to Methimazole to avoid PTU-induced hepatotoxicity.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B & C: Methimazole and Carbimazole are teratogenic in the first trimester.</li><li>Option D: Propranolol is for symptomatic control, not the primary treatment for the thyroid status.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N393", stem: "Identify the degree of tear shown below.", img: "", ans_key: "C", options: ["1st degree", "2nd degree", "3rd degree", "4th degree"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>A 3rd-degree perineal tear involves the vaginal mucosa, perineal skin, perineal muscles, and extends into the anal sphincter complex (EAS/IAS) but does not involve the rectal mucosa. The description matches the involvement of the sphincter.<br><br><img src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgpKjuYHxA9E3oORkG5Yk4cTAv0eRmFe2eFG77leMqGX3LvI3JadGaVbz2DMvZBr7utBjfRG47DESn7poudPyM2h_VNcEC-ZkrRcSfDLzf9T5xRIY-d6SFYFNat9GVh0RAozL8fq0w0tZqFATMJUtLiaNPL95aZckBzn5i-5sTY0pOpfVKZXprXxBPXlPo/s188/d5faeb95-c5a1-4348-a9b2-7b1bbed2fe33.jpg' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Involves only skin/mucosa.</li><li>Option B: Involves muscles but spares the sphincter.</li><li>Option D: Involves rectal mucosa.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N394", stem: "A 14 year old girl presents with a history of primary amenorrhea. On physical examination, an imperforate hymen is observed. What karyotype analysis would you consider for further evaluation?", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["46XY", "46XX", "45XO", "47XXY"], subject: "Gynecology", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>An imperforate hymen is an outflow tract obstruction in a genetic female. The karyotype is normal female, 46XX. The ovaries and uterus are usually normal, leading to cryptomenorrhea (hidden bleeding).<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: 46XY is seen in Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome (no uterus).</li><li>Option C: 45XO is Turner syndrome (ovarian dysgenesis).</li><li>Option D: 47XXY is Klinefelter syndrome (male).</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N395", stem: "What is the preferred method of delivery in A cephalic lie and B cephalic lie?", img: "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh71vawzjsFvjNpLkIdBgMQoHOpIKU-1EA91T42aTTp-Y1iQUWFnoHIewWVkUnTStWaduw2oF2_27IAkVblOEkcwJ5JKEJCFqkSMeZ1AUi5zE7Ee3splfBEf1r36vkZ6s8FFYV-Dv08uVwJDuVJbW9xMcQJL0ZvKbfqyph-PNcpv3Sr-3sTRmyqj8waVjg/s1026/787b7d2c-30d3-4fd0-a6f1-df0dc716fb16.png", ans_key: "C", options: ["LSCS, vaginal", "Vaginal, LSCS", "Normal delivery in both", "LSCS in both"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>In a twin pregnancy where both twins (Twin A and Twin B) are in cephalic (vertex) presentation, vaginal delivery is typically the preferred and safe method for both, barring other complications.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Options A, B, and D: Cesarean section (LSCS) is not routinely indicated if both twins are cephalic.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N396", stem: "What is the typical time between fertilization and implantation in human reproduction?", img: "", ans_key: "B", options: ["2 days", "8 days", "14 days", "16 days"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Implantation typically begins around 6-7 days after fertilization and is well-established by day 8-10. Therefore, 8 days is the most accurate answer among the choices.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option A: Too early (embryo is in tubes).</li><li>Option C & D: By day 14, the missed period occurs; implantation is already complete.</li></ul>" },
{ q: "N397", stem: "During ovulation, what is released?", img: "", ans_key: "A", options: ["Secondary oocyte at the end of meiosis I", "Secondary oocyte at the end of meiosis II", "Primary oocyte at the end of meiosis I", "Primary oocyte at the end of meiosis II"], subject: "Obstetrics", exam: "NEET PG", year_paper: "2024 Shift 1", explanation: "<strong>Solution</strong><br>Just prior to ovulation, the primary oocyte completes Meiosis I to form the secondary oocyte and the first polar body. The secondary oocyte then arrests in Metaphase II. It is this secondary oocyte (at the end of Meiosis I / arrested in Meiosis II) that is released.<br><br><img src=' ' onclick='openImageModal(this.src)' class='cursor-zoom-in hover:opacity-90 transition' style='max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin-top: 10px; border-radius: 8px;' /><br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><ul><li>Option B: Meiosis II is only completed after fertilization.</li><li>Option C: The primary oocyte divides *before* ovulation.</li></ul>" },
];
